## Discriminated union pattern

`AnySectionT` in `sections.ts` is a discriminated union on the `type` literal field:

```ts
export type AnySectionT =
  | HeroSectionT           // type: "hero"
  | CardsSectionT          // type: "cards"
  | AudiencePromoCardSectionT  // type: "audience_promo_card"
  // ... 49 more
  | TeamBehindSalonoraSectionT; // type: "team_behind_salonora"
```

TypeScript narrows the union automatically in any `switch (section.type)` block. The `default: assertNever(section)` pattern turns missing cases into **compile errors**, not silent runtime bugs.

```ts
// src/lib/utils/assert-never.ts
export function assertNever(value: never): never {
  throw new Error(`Unhandled case: ${JSON.stringify(value)}`);
}
```

Both `SectionRenderer.tsx` and `mapKnownPageSectionLayout()` in `normalize-page-sections.ts` use this pattern. When adding a new type to `AnySectionT`, the build will fail until both switch statements have the new case.

